<th>1</th>\n      <td>book_00001_2024-03-02</td>\n      <td>49.0</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>2</th>\n      <td>book_00001_2024-03-03</td>\n      <td>60.0</td>\n    </tr>\n    <tr>\n      <th>3</th>\n      <td>book_00001_2024-03-04</td>\n      <td>50.0</td>\n    </tr>\n  </tbody>\n</table>\n</div>"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":57},{"cell_type":"code","source":"submission.audience_count.mean()","metadata":{"trusted":true,"execution":{"iopub.status.busy":"2025-11-30T16:31:17.761955Z","iopub.execute_input":"2025-11-30T16:31:17.762199Z","iopub.status.idle":"2025-11-30T16:31:17.768326Z","shell.execute_reply.started":"2025-11-30T16:31:17.762184Z","shell.execute_reply":"2025-11-30T16:31:17.767417Z"}},"outputs":[{"execution_count":58,"output_type":"execute_result","data":{"text/plain":"43.705874625610846"},"metadata":{}}],"execution_count":58},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"**Final Model Interpretation:**\n\nAmong the boosting models tested, XGBoost delivered the best predictive accuracy. It achieved the lowest MAE and RMSE and the highest R² on both the training and validation datasets. The drop from training to validation performance was small, indicating the model generalizes well without severe overfitting. Hence, performed hyper-parameter tuning with XGBoost model and submitted it for final prediction.\n\nLightGBM and HistGradientBoosting also performed reasonably well, with all models showing stable behaviour. R² values around 0.50–0.60 indicate that audience count is influenced by multiple external factors not fully captured in the dataset, yet the models are able to explain a significant portion of the variability.\n","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"## General learning about Time series data: reference\n\n1. Weekly Seasonality (Weekend effect)\n\nFriday, Saturday, Sunday → audience usually higher\n\nMonday–Thursday → lower\n\n2. Monthly / Seasonal Trends\n\nSummer holidays → more audience\n\nExam months → less audience\n\n3. Festival / Holiday Peaks\n\nDiwali, Pongal, Christmas → ticket sales spike\n\nImpact is huge but not captured unless you add a feature.\n\n4. New Movie Release Days\n\nFriday has a sudden rise\n\nNext 2–3 days also higher\n\nAfter day 5, audience drops\n\n5. Continuous Patterns (Lag effects)\n\nYesterday’s audience affects today’s audience.\nLast week (same weekday) also influences today.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"code","source":"#Verify the file exists before submission\n!ls -lh /kaggle/working","metadata":{"trusted":true},"outputs":[],"execution_count":null},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"Boosting models automatically learn:\n\nWeekends > weekdays\n\nFestival days > normal days\n\nOpening day spikes\n\nDecline after a few days\n\nTheatre-wise capacity differences\n\nShow date → seasonal effects\n\nRolling features → trend\n\nLag features → autocorrelation\n\nLinear models cannot learn these interactions without heavy manual feature engineering.","metadata":{}},{"cell_type":"markdown","source":"“I chose boosting models because my cinema audience data has strong non-linear patterns influenced by weekends, holidays, movie releases, and theatre IDs. Boosting models learn these complex relationships better than linear or bagging models.\n\nBoosting works by sequentially adding small decision trees, each correcting the previous tree’s error. This makes the final model highly accurate.\n\nTechniques like XGBoost, LightGBM, and HistGradientBoosting are perfect for tabular, feature-rich forecasting tasks and consistently outperform linear models, ARIMA, and Random Forest for this dataset.”","metadata":{}}]}